blocks.content: Define the class of totally bounded metrics. A metric space is totally bounded iff it can be covered by a finite number of balls of any given radius. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-totbnd(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4, setvar s5) {
  |- wceq(ctotbnd, cmpt(s0, universe, crab(s1, cfv(cmet, cv(s0)), wral(s2, crp, wrex(s3, cfn, wa(wceq(cuni(cv(s3)), cv(s0)), wral(s4, cv(s3), wrex(s5, cv(s0), wceq(cv(s4), co(cv(s5), cfv(cbl, cv(s1)), cv(s2)))))))))))
  -| diffss(s2, s4)
  -| diffss(s1, s4)
  -| diffss(s3, s4)
  -| diffss(s0, s4)
  -| diffss(s4, s5)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s2, s5)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s1, s5)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s3, s5)
  -| diffss(s0, s5)
}

axiom df-totbnd(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, setvar s4, setvar s5) {
  ‚ä¢ TotBnd =(s0 ‚àà ùïå ‚Ü¶ { s1 ‚àà(Met ` s0)| ‚àÄ(s2 ‚àà ‚Ñù+, ‚àÉ(s3 ‚àà Fin,(‚ãÉ s3 = s0 ‚àß ‚àÄ(s4 ‚àà s3, ‚àÉ(s5 ‚àà s0, s4 =(s5[(ball ` s1)]s2))))))})
  ‚ä£ d(s2, s4)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s4)
  ‚ä£ d(s3, s4)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s4)
  ‚ä£ d(s4, s5)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s2)
  ‚ä£ d(s2, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s2)
  ‚ä£ d(s2, s5)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s3)

  ‚ä£ d(s1, s5)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s3, s5)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s5)
}

blocks.name: totbndmet
blocks.content: The predicate "totally bounded" implies ` M ` is a metric space. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.)
blocks.origin:
thm totbndmet(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wcel(c0, cfv(ctotbnd, c1)), wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)))

blocks.name: sstotbnd
blocks.content: Condition for a subset of a metric space to be totally bounded. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 12-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: equivtotbnd
blocks.content: If the metric ` M ` is "strongly finer" than ` N ` (meaning that there is a positive real constant ` R ` such that ` N ( x , y ) <_ R x. M ( x , y ) ` ), then total boundedness of ` M ` implies total boundedness of ` N ` . (Using this theorem twice in each direction states that if two metrics are strongly equivalent, then one is totally bounded iff the other is.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 14-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: df-bnd
blocks.content: Define the class of bounded metrics. A metric space is bounded iff it can be covered by a single ball. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.)
blocks.origin:
axiom df-bnd(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3) {
  |- wceq(cbnd, cmpt(s0, universe, crab(s1, cfv(cmet, cv(s0)), wral(s2, cv(s0), wrex(s3, crp, wceq(cv(s0), co(cv(s2), cfv(cbl, cv(s1)), cv(s3))))))))
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
}
blocks.pretty:
axiom df-bnd(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3) {
  ‚ä¢ Bnd =(s0 ‚àà ùïå ‚Ü¶ { s1 ‚àà(Met ` s0)| ‚àÄ(s2 ‚àà s0, ‚àÉ(s3 ‚àà ‚Ñù+, s0 =(s2[(ball ` s1)]s3)))})
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s1)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, s2)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s2, s3)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s2)
}

blocks.name: bndmet
blocks.content: A bounded metric space is a metric space. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 16-Sep-2015.)

blocks.content: A "bounded extended metric" (meaning that it satisfies the same condition as a bounded metric, but with "metric" replaced with "extended metric") is a metric and thus is bounded in the conventional sense. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 12-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: isbnd3b
blocks.content: A metric space is bounded iff the metric function maps to some bounded real interval. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 22-Sep-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm isbnd3b(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, class c0, class c1) {
  |- wb(wcel(c0, cfv(cbnd, c1)), wa(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wrex(s0, cr, wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wbr(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), cle, cv(s0)))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c0)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s2, c0)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
} = {
  bitri(wcel(c0, cfv(cbnd, c1)), wa(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wrex(s0, cr, wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wbr(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), cle, cv(s0)))))), wa(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wrex(s0, cr, wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0))))))
  isbnd3(s0, c0, c1)
  pm5.32i(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wrex(s0, cr, wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0)))), wrex(s0, cr, wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wbr(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), cle, cv(s0))))))
  rexbidva(s0, cr, wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0))), wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wbr(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), cle, cv(s0)))))
  bitrd(wa(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wcel(cv(s0), cr)), wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0))), wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wbr(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), cle, cv(s0)))), wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wcel(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0))))))
  3syl(wa(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wcel(cv(s0), cr)), wb(wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0))), wral(s1, c1, wral(s2, c1, wcel(co(cv(s1), c0, cv(s2)), co(nat0, cicc, cv(s0)))))), wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), cr), wfn(c0, cxp(c1, c1)))
  adantr(wcel(c0, cfv(cmet, c1)), wcel(cv(s0), cr), wf(c0, cxp(c1, c1), cr))
  metf(c0, c1)
  ffn(c0, cxp(c1, c1), cr)

blocks.name: totbndbnd
blocks.content: A totally bounded metric space is bounded. This theorem fails for extended metrics - a bounded extended metric is a metric, but there are totally bounded extended metrics that are not metrics (if we were to weaken ~ istotbnd to only require that ` M ` be an extended metric). A counterexample is the discrete extended metric (assigning distinct points distance ` +oo ` ) on a finite set. (Contributed by Jeff Madsen, 2-Sep-2009.) (Proof shortened by Mario Carneiro, 12-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: equivbnd
blocks.content: If the metric ` M ` is "strongly finer" than ` N ` (meaning that there is a positive real constant ` R ` such that ` N ( x , y ) <_ R x. M ( x , y ) ` ), then boundedness of ` M ` implies boundedness of ` N ` . (Using this theorem twice in each direction states that if two metrics are strongly equivalent, then one is bounded iff the other is.) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 14-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: prdsbnd
blocks.content: The product metric over finite index set is bounded if all the factors are bounded. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 13-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: prdstotbnd
blocks.content: The product metric over finite index set is totally bounded if all the factors are totally bounded. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 20-Sep-2015.)

blocks.name: prdsbnd2
blocks.content: If balls are totally bounded in each factor, then balls are bounded in a metric product. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 16-Sep-2015.)
